Self-Supervised Learning on CIFAR-10 (SIGReg + BCS)
This project implements a self-supervised learning (SSL) framework on CIFAR-10 using a custom BCS
(Batched Characteristic Slicing) loss inspired by SIGReg, combined with a linear probe for evaluation.

Overview
Backbone: Custom lightweight ResNet-like architecture (ResNeTiny)
SSL Objective: Invariance loss (MSE) + BCS loss (Gaussianity regularization)
Evaluation: Online linear probe
Dataset: CIFAR-10
Logging: Optional Weights & Biases (wandb)

Installation
pip install torch torchvision tqdm wandb

Training
Run training:
python main.py
Enable Weights & Biases logging:
python main.py --wandb True

Method
Each image is transformed into two random views using standard augmentations such as random resized crop, color jitter, grayscale, and horizontal flip.
Total loss:
L = L_invariance + λ * L_BCS
L_invariance: Mean Squared Error between embeddings
L_BCS: Encourages Gaussian-distributed features using random projections

Evaluation
A linear classifier (probe) is trained on frozen features to measure representation quality.

Output
- Training loss (SSL + linear probe)
- Validation accuracy
- Saved checkpoint including backbone, probe, and optimizer

Visualization
The script generates views_visualization.png showing augmented crops.

Notes
- Designed for experimentation with self-supervised learning
- Lightweight and fast training
- Easily extendable

Future Improvements
- Add projection head (MLP)
- Try cosine similarity loss
- Stronger augmentations
- Scale backbone

